<text>Deleting atoms

&lt; Previous | Index | Next &gt;

There are several methods to remove atoms. The first one is to press the &quot; &quot; button on the tool bar, and then drag the mouse to draw a rectangular area. All the atoms that are visually within it will be removed when the mouse is released. This tool allows you to quickly remove many atoms at a time.

If you right-click (or CTRL+click on Mac OS X without a multiple-button mouse) on the button, you will see a pop-up menu, from which you can select the tool for removing atoms in an oval area. You will see that the image on the button changes to &quot; &quot;, indicating that an oval area will be selected.

If you just need to remove a few atoms from different location, right-click (or CTRL+click on Mac OS X without a multiple-button mouse) on an atom, and then select &quot;Cut&quot; from the pop-up menu. You can also select the &quot; &quot; button, click on an atom, and then hit CTRL+X (Windows) or Command+X (Mac OS X), or the Backspace or Delete key.

